# Project: FastAPI Backend – OpenAI Integration (Responses API)

This repository is a production-grade FastAPI backend integrating OpenAI (Responses API).
The service must be secure, observable, and testable.

## Test Gate Policy

This project follows strict test gating.

1. Pre-condition:
   - Confirm the current test suite passes before implementing changes.
   - If not, warn and stop.

2. Post-condition:
   - Run the full test suite after implementing changes.
   - Do not consider the task complete if any test fails.

A feature is complete only when:
- All tests pass
- No new warnings or regressions are introduced

Use the test command defined in the project (e.g. `pytest`) to verify correctness.

## Documentation Gate (Mandatory)

No task is considered complete unless documentation is consistent with the implemented changes.

Before marking a task as complete:

1. Identify all documentation impacted by the change:
   - README
   - API documentation (OpenAPI / docstrings)
   - Architecture notes
   - Configuration instructions
   - Environment variables
   - Runbooks (if relevant)

2. Update documentation to reflect:
   - New endpoints
   - Changed behavior
   - New environment variables
   - New dependencies
   - Breaking changes
   - Updated workflows

3. Ensure examples and code snippets (if any) match the current implementation.

A task is complete only when:
- All tests are green
- Documentation reflects the current state of the system
- No outdated references remain

If documentation is missing or unclear, propose the minimal necessary addition.

Documentation updates must be proportional to the change.
Do not introduce unnecessary verbosity or redundant files.
Prefer updating existing documents over creating new ones.

## Expected Stack & Practices
- FastAPI with APIRouter and dependency injection (Depends)
- Pydantic v2 + pydantic-settings for configuration (.env)
- Official OpenAI Python client (preferred)
- Async-first architecture (use async/await if the app is async; do not mix sync and async)
- Testing with pytest (+ pytest-asyncio if async)
- Respect existing lint/format tools (ruff, black, mypy if present)

## Recommended Structure (if not already defined)
app/
  main.py
  core/        (config, logging, errors)
  api/         (deps, routes)
  schemas/     (request/response models)
  services/    (OpenAI wrapper + business logic)
tests/

Do not introduce new structure unless necessary. Follow the repo’s existing structure.

## OpenAI Integration Rules (Mandatory)
- API keys must come from environment variables (OPENAI_API_KEY). Never hardcode.
- Use timeouts for all external calls.
- Handle rate limits and transient errors (basic retry with backoff if needed).
- Never log full prompts or sensitive user data.
- Apply data minimization when sending data to OpenAI.
- Use structured, consistent response envelopes.
- Streaming only if explicitly requested.

## Observability Requirements
- Include request_id, endpoint, status_code, and latency in logs.
- Use middleware for request_id and timing if not already implemented.
- Centralized exception handling preferred over scattered try/except blocks.

## Implementation Guidelines
When implementing a new feature:
1. Define endpoint(s)
2. Define Pydantic request/response schemas
3. Implement service layer logic
4. Handle errors explicitly
5. Add minimal tests

Keep routers thin.
Business logic belongs in services/.
Validation belongs in schemas.
Avoid framework over-engineering.

## Coding Style
- Explicit type hints on public functions.
- Clear naming (no cryptic abbreviations).
- Short architectural comments (ADR-style) only when a decision matters.